      "source": [
        "# Neutrino Interaction position Reconstruction with GNNs\n",
        "For this exercise, we are solving a regression problem:\n",
        "\n",
        "(x\n",
        "true\n",
        ",y\n",
        "true\t​\n",
        ")→(x\n",
        "pred\n",
        ",y\n",
        "pred\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "For this purpose, we developed a Graph Neural Network (GNN), for reconstructing neutrino interaction positions. The process consists of environment setup, data handling, model definition, training, visualization, and hyperparameter tuning.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Key Steps:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  **Environment Setup:**\n",
        "    *   Installed and configured necessary libraries including `awkward`, `torch_geometric`, and related PyG components\n",
        "\n",
        "2.  **Data Loading and Normalization:**\n",
        "    *   Loaded neutrino interaction data from parquet files (`train.pq`, `val.pq`, `test.pq`) using `awkward`.\n",
        "    *   Implemented helper functions to compute mean and standard deviation for normalization based on the training dataset.\n",
        "    *   Applied min-max normalization to input features (hit times, x, y positions) and target values (interaction x, y positions).\n",
        "\n",
        "3.  **Custom Dataset and DataLoader:**\n",
        "    *   Created a custom `AwkwardDataset` to efficiently handle `awkward` arrays with `torch.utils.data.DataLoader`.\n",
        "    *   Developed a `collate_fn_gnn` to convert `awkward` records into `torch_geometric.data.Batch` objects suitable for GNN input.\n",
        "\n",
        "4.  **GNN Model Definition:**\n",
        "    *   Defined the `GNNEncoder` class, utilizing `DynamicEdgeConv` layers for feature aggregation and a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) for final position regression. Used two EdgeConv layers at first. Later identified three layers structure more effective for  improved poerformance of the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "5.  **Training and Evaluation:**\n",
        "    *   Set up a standard training loop with `Adam` optimizer and `MSELoss` criterion.\n",
        "    *   Implemented `train_epoch` and `evaluate` functions to manage the training and validation process.\n",
        "    *   Trained the model for 30 epochs and tracked training and validation loss, and validation Mean Absolute Error (MAE).\n",
        "\n",
        "6.  **Post-Training Analysis and Visualizations:**\n",
        "    *   Generated a training curve plot showing loss over epochs.\n",
        "    *   Created scatter plots of predicted vs. true X and Y positions, including a `y=x` reference line.\n",
        "    *   Plotted residual histograms for X and Y positions, displaying mean, standard deviation, and a comparison to a normal distribution.\n",
        "    \n",
        "  and some more of them for added analysis and understanding.\n",
        "  \n",
        "\n",
        "7.  **Hyperparameter Tuning with Optuna:**\n",
        "    *   Integrated Optuna, an automatic hyperparameter optimization framework, to tune the `learning_rate` and `k_neighbors` parameters of the GNN.\n",
        "    *   Defined an `objective` function to train and evaluate the model for each trial, returning the validation MAE.\n",
        "    *   Ran an Optuna study with 20 trials, identifying the following best parameters:\n",
        "        *   `learning_rate`: `0.000990488483276294`\n",
        "        *   `k_neighbors`: `10`\n",
        "        *   Optimal validation MAE: `0.18593010306358337`\n",
        "\n",
        "8. **Updated the model with optimal hyperparameters:**\n",
